{
  "answer": "**Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1**\n\nThis narrative appears in the *Āṅgirasa Smṛti* (slug: *unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1*), Chapter 1.[^1]\n\n**Verbatim quote of the weighing:**\n\n> Placing all these in one scale-pan, the lotus-born (Brahmā), placing the *panasa* (पनस) in the other pan, weighed them with his hand. // Ang_1.531 // Then the *panasa* (पनस) became slightly heavier.[^2]\n\n**Verbatim quote of the three numerical equivalences:**\n\n> The *bṛhatī* (बृहती, eggplant) then became equal to three hundred, in the sight of all. // Ang_1.532 // Ginger (*ārdraka*) was equal to six hundred, and sesame (*tila*) was equal to one hundred. Thus, this trio was established on the balance scale from that day onwards. // Ang_1.533 //[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-4fe9a6).\n\n[^3]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-675fe0).",
